<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">08, Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Holding cabinet repair, what LA operators ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What's a holding cabinet vs a warming cabinet?</h3>
        <p>Same equipment, terminology varies by region. "Holding cabinet" is the most common term and matches FDA Food Code language. "Warming cabinet" gets used commercially. "Heated cabinet" is the generic term. All three refer to an insulated heated cabinet maintaining cooked food at safe holding temperatures (140°F minimum) between cooking and service.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why does Alto-Shaam dominate 70%+ of the holding cabinet market?</h3>
        <p>Halo Heat technology. Radiant heating elements distribute gentle heat throughout the cabinet without fan circulation, which means food stays moist instead of drying out during 4 to 8 hour holds. The result is preserved food quality plus reliable temperature uniformity. We service the full Alto-Shaam Halo Heat lineup: 1000-S, 750-S, 500-S, plus mobile carts 500-2D and 1200-TH/III.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My holding cabinet temperature drifts below 140°F. Is that an FDA compliance issue?</h3>
        <p>Yes. FDA Food Code requires hot food holding at 140°F minimum. Below that line is a food safety violation and a potential health code issue at your next inspection. The most likely cause is thermostat drift, typical at year 5 to 8 of cabinet life. Recalibration runs $290 to $440. Replacement runs $440 to $720. Fix immediately for FDA compliance, this is not a problem to defer.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is Halo Heat technology?</h3>
        <p>Alto-Shaam specialty. Radiant heating elements distribute gentle heat throughout the cabinet without fan circulation. No air movement that dries food, more uniform temperature distribution, and preserved food quality during long holding periods. Halo Heat element replacement runs $480 to $720 per element, typical lifespan 8 to 12 years.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My mobile holding cart wheels are worn out. Replace the cart or fix?</h3>
        <p>Almost always fix. Cres Cor and Alto-Shaam mobile carts have replaceable casters at $80 to $180 per wheel. The cabinet bodies last 12 to 15+ years easily. New cart replacement runs $4,000 to $8,000+. The math always favors caster replacement, except in the rare case where the chassis frame itself is bent from a forklift incident.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Winston CVap vs Alto-Shaam Halo Heat, which is better?</h3>
        <p>Different technologies, different value propositions. Halo Heat is radiant dry heat, simpler, lower upfront cost ($4,000 to $8,000), proven reliability across high-volume LA banquet kitchens. CVap is controlled vapor with humidity preservation, better for moisture-sensitive foods (delicate proteins, vegetables), higher upfront ($8,000 to $15,000), more complex maintenance with the water injection system. Both serviceable, the choice depends on what you hold.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can you service Alto-Shaam Combitherm with holding mode?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Combitherm combi ovens have an integrated holding mode and we service both the combi side (steam plus convection) and the holding mode. See our <a href="/commercial/oven-repair/combi-oven-repair/" style="color:var(--red);">combi oven repair page</a> for combi-specific service. Same Alto-Shaam authorized parts network covers both product lines.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What's your warranty?</h3>
        <p>90 days SDAR labor warranty on every commercial holding cabinet repair. OEM parts carry the manufacturer's own warranty (typically 90 days to 1 year depending on the component), processed separately through the brand's service network. We document every part number installed.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

